  "opinion": "As a curious electrician who's spent decades working on the electrical systems that power Philadelphia's homes and businesses, I've seen firsthand how stereotypes can quietly undermine people's potential. Stereotype threat isn't some abstract academic concept—it's the anxiety that comes when someone feels their group identity might be judged negatively in a high-stakes environment. For instance, when I've worked with young women or minority students in technical roles, I've noticed how the fear of not measuring up can make them hesitate to ask questions or take on challenging tasks. This isn't about innate ability; it's about the psychological weight of being labeled 'not the right kind' for a job that requires precision and problem-solving. Should we address it? Absolutely. In my experience, the best way is through consistent, respectful dialogue and creating environments where everyone feels safe to learn without fear of judgment. I've seen this work when I've encouraged my own kids—both boys and girls—to explore science and engineering through hands-on projects like building circuits or fixing appliances. It's not about changing the system overnight but making small, intentional choices every day: listening to concerns, celebrating diverse talents, and modeling confidence without arrogance. The key is to recognize that stereotype threat isn't a barrier to be overcome by forcing people into a mold but a challenge to be met with empathy and practical support. After all, in the electrical trade, where every connection matters, we don't want to let any potential talent go unheard.",
